<div class="live-post__wrapper-body-article">
<h3 class="live-post__title">From number one to nothing to do: UK musicians on surviving the pandemic
</h3>
<div class="articleBodyText section">
<div class="article-body-text component  ">
<div class="component-content">
<p><span class="m_first-letter m_first-letter--flagged">O</span>n New Year’s Eve 2019, fast rising UK indie band BLOXX were huddled in a London club, waiting for the countdown. Front woman Ophelia Booth formed the band in 2016 while studying music technology in West London and working part-time at her local Wetherspoons.</p>
<p>When their first single, Your Boyfriend, went viral, she took the plunge into music full-time, quitting her job and her degree to support The Wombats and Two Door Cinema Club on tour while preparing their debut album. “This year,” Booth whispered to her bandmates Mozwin, Taz and Paul on the final night of 2019, “is going to be our year. This year is going to make us.”</p>
<p>Three months later, as Covid-19 spread across the globe and flattened life as we know it, BLOXX reeled in collective shock. How could they promote their debut album without touring it? How could they make their music videos without seeing each other? And more importantly, how would they make ends meet?</p>
<p><a href="https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/artists/number-one-nothing-do-uk-musicians-surviving-pandemic/"><strong>Eleanor Halls</strong> meets the talents whose careers are suffering from coronavirus</a></p>
